I started this journey a little over 8 years ago.

I failed at home workouts prior and always said they were for me! I was a former athlete. A runner. I new what to do, I didn’t need to follow a video.

I lived uncomfortable in my skin.

I didnt know how to eat properly and just really had the goal of trying to eat less.

In July 2014, I had my daughter. I had no idea how I would lose the baby weight plus the other 15lbs I needed to lose. Would I ever feel good in my skin again.

I got invited to a bootcamp and said no.
I can do it on my own.

4 months down the road, winter was approaching. I could no longer run outside with a infant in harsh Minnesota winters. Our gym didn’t have childcare. I still had no idea how to eat properly.

So I finally said yes.

I had no idea what that one yes would mean.

I found freedom in my food journey.
I found a effective workout at home, plus I can still run when Im able to.
I found a community.
I found support.
I found out, I wasn’t alone.

I’m opening up my next bootcamp, we start Jan 2nd. If your looking for a solution or needing some support this season, I’d love for you to join me. Either send me a message or drop a comment “SURETHING” and I’ll send you info!

Tell me if this sounds familiar…

Your mornings are a hot mess. Your sleep schedule and sleep quality is shit. You’re repeatedly hitting the snooze button in an effort to sleep in just 5 more minutes (please)… over and over again. You wake up with a headache, in a bad mood, and as if that wasn’t enough, you’re now also running late! So, you finally hop out of bed, rush to get ready and get out the door, nothing seems to go right, you’re stressed out and your stomach is grumbling in anger. It’s not even 9 a.m. yet and you’re already counting down the minutes until you get off work. You swear you’ll get your shit together, go to bed at a reasonable time tonight, and get up earlier tomorrow so that you don’t have to rush and can actually start the day off on the right foot. You even score a win here and there but for the most part, every morning seems just as worse as the last. You feel stuck in a never-ending loop of chaotic mornings and wish you could just catch a break.

Been there?

Girl, me too! And I realized, after riding that rollercoaster one too many times, that if I truly wanted to break from the cycle and stop feeling so drained and moody all the time and actually have less hectic mornings, something really had to change.

It wasn’t until I was intentional and changed my entire morning routine that I was able to actually see positive long-term results in my sleep quality, my energy levels, my mood, and my anxiety. Which is why this month I am hosting a free 5 day virtual workshop called Rise and Shine.

Every day for 5 days, I will be sharing some of my most valuable lessons and tips to help you take back control of your mornings in small simple steps, escape the repetitive snooze trap once and for all, and start your day off on the right foot! 

If you’re ready to trade in the crazy mornings for a morning routine that you actually look forward to, that makes you feel good, and creates real and lasting change in your life, drop a ✨ below and I’ll get you the info!

Imagine having more patience with your children, having a more positive outlook on life, being able to problem-solve more effectively, being able to appreciate the opportunities that are available to you, getting ahead on your projects without the mental blocks, feeling valued, accomplished, being able to express your creativity, starting the day peacefully… doesn’t that sound so much better?

I mean, when you consider the alternative, the chaos, stress, anxiety, the rush, the running late, the headaches, the sugar cravings, the afternoon crash, the lack of energy or motivation, the irritability, emotional blow-ups... it’s really a no-brainer! We weren’t meant to struggle so much, feel “blah”, or like we’re spiraling out of control. We shouldn’t be staring at the clock every two minutes, wishing we could just go home and have a nap.

That’s not normal.

But it is common for too many. 

The good news? It doesn’t have to be your reality any longer!

Next week, I am hosting a free 5 day workshop where I am going to teach you how to create an effective morning routine that you can easily implement and benefit from right away! 

Every day for 5 days, we’ll get together to break down a few key simple behaviours that will transform your mornings from disorganized and chaotic to serene and productive. I’ll also be sharing some of the tools and resources that helped me escape the repetitive snooze trap and how you can develop an early morning routine that will work for you so you can go on about your day with your best foot forward.

Over 5 days, I am going to share:

✨ Why you should create a solid (early) morning routine 
✨ How a successful morning routine actually starts the evening before
✨ 5 tips to avoid the snooze trap
✨ What to do once you’re up (and how to make the most of it)
✨ How to own your mornings (rather than having your mornings own you!)

If you’re ready to drop the struggle and finally create real and lasting change, drop a ✨ below and I’ll get you the info!

“If you don’t like where you are, move! You are not a tree.”

I love this quote by Jim Rohn because it reminds me that if I want something to change, I have to change it or change myself. I am not stuck. I am in control of my actions, my reactions, and ultimately, my life. 

Sometimes, we need to take big action and make big moves. Other times, all it takes is small shifts to make the world of a difference.

If you’re ready to improve your morning routine and go from tired, rushed, and hectic to quiet, peaceful, and productive, you don’t want to miss this!

Easy Homemade Bagels

I made these gluten free but you total could use any type of flour you prefer. PLUS, they were super easy. 

1 cup Greek Yogurt (I used non-fat)
1 cup GF flour
2 tsp Baking Powder
1/4 tsp Salt
1 egg white
Everything But the Bagel Seasoning… again you could use any seasoning you want. 

Preheat your oven to 375. 
Combine the flour, baking powder and salt in a m mixing bowl. Add in the yogurt and stir until combined, in should result in crumbles. 

Dust a clean surface with a touch of flour, remove the flour from the mixing bowl and place on the clean surface to knead until the touch is tacky. Dough should not stick to your hands. 
Divide the mixture into 4 balls and roll each one out to about 3-4 inches long. Join the ends together to form a bagel.
Whisk the egg white in a bowl then wash each bagel with it. Top with seasoning. 
Bake 25-29 minutes or until lightly browned around the edges. 

These are so easy and delicious, plus not loaded with tons of calories.

 We are jumping right into with day one!
Today we are tackling the pantry. 

 Love it or hate, the pantry is a vital part of every kitchen and therefore causes chaos when it’s not well organized. Don’t worry, we’re not going for Pinterest perfect or beautifully matched and decorated. 

 The key with everything this week is function. 

What good are all those healthy snacks if you can’t even see them or access them easily enough to actually eat them? How are you supposed to create a habit of cooking healthier homemade meals when it’s a huge hassle to even find the ingredients you need? 

From baking items to canned goods, pasta, seasonings, tea and coffee and snacks, your pantry is the workhorse of the kitchen. Whether it’s a closet, large cupboard or entire room, it needs to be clean and organized.
So, let’s get to it! 

1. Empty out the entire pantry. Take everything out. There should be literally nothing left unless it is bolted into the wall or floor.
2. Throw out old food. This includes expired items and also anything that got left open. There may be half eaten bags of chips or boxes of crackers that have gone stale. Just throw it out.
3. Get rid of things. If you haven’t used it in the past 6 months, you likely never will. All that canned coconut milk might have sounded like a good idea until you realized you don’t even like it. Donate it to a food pantry or give it to someone who will use it.
4. Clean the pantry. Wipe down all the shelves and then vacuum or sweep the floor or bottom of the pantry.
5. Group items together. Gather all your baking items together. Consolidate all the pasta. Put all the snacks in one bin or box. Create simple categories that make sense for how you will use the items.
6. Put everything back. Keep similar items together and put things back in an organized manner. Use boxes or bins to put the grouped items in for easier access. Label everything that is not in original packaging as well as any categorized bins.

One of my biggest road blocks in a healthy lifestyle was not meal planning.

BREAKFAST
For breakfast I usually pick one or two meal prep egg, oatmeal or yogurt recipes that I can make ahead of time and grab and go. Then I always have a fun yummy, carb filled Saturday morning breakfast.

LUNCH
I plan out two options for the week. Usually chicken based and with lots of veggies. Again super easy and quick options.

DINNER
I typically follow this format:

Monday: Sheet Pan or Crockpot Meal
Tuesday: Taco Tuesday (or some kind of Mexican Dish)
Wednesday: Asian/Oriental Dish
Thursday: Soup/Salad/or Sandwiches
Friday: Pizza or Burgers

This gives us a variety and then on the weekends we do leftovers.

Fall means soup to me.

This version of chicken wild rice soup is so simple and quick.

Ingredients
1 rotisserie chicken or 3 c cooked chicken
1 can wild rice
4 tbls butter
1 tbls flour
1 onion diced 
1 carrot shredded
2 stalks celery diced
3 c chicken broth
1 c water 
1 c cream
Seasonings: I used salt, pepper, garlic salt, poultry seasoning, parsley, and sage

Sauté onion, celery and carrots in butter. While you are doing that shred your chicken.
When onions are translucent add in flour (if you want thicker soup add more flour). 
Stir together.
Add broth and water.
Add chicken and wild rice (if you can’t find canned wild rice you can use 1 box uncle bens wild rice - this will just mean you need to cook a little longer). 
Add seasonings.
Let simmer for 10-15 minutes
Add in cream and let simmer and thicken for 5-10 minutes.

Serve and enjoy!

INGREDIENTS

* 1 tsp sage

INSTRUCTIONS
* Spray the crockpot with non stick cooking spray

* Next top the chicken with the stuffing mix .
* In a separate bowl, mix together the broth and sour cream. The sour cream is optional. It makes everything a little more creamy. Top this mixture over the dry stuffing mix. Top with seasonings
* Add butter on top
* The last layer will be the frozen green beans or a can of drained green beans
* Cook on high for 4 hours or cook on low for about 7 to 8 hours.
* When done fluff the stuffing with a fork and serve. 
* I served with a salad.

I started this journey a little over 8 years ago.

I failed at home workouts prior and always said they were for me! I was a former athlete. A runner. I new what to do, I didn’t need to follow a video.

I lived uncomfortable in my skin.

I didnt know how to eat properly and just really had the goal of trying to eat less.

In July 2014, I had my daughter. I had no idea how I would lose the baby weight plus the other 15lbs I needed to lose. Would I ever feel good in my skin again.

I got invited to a bootcamp and said no.
I can do it on my own.

4 months down the road, winter was approaching. I could no longer run outside with a infant in harsh Minnesota winters. Our gym didn’t have childcare. I still had no idea how to eat properly.

So I finally said yes.

I had no idea what that one yes would mean.

I found freedom in my food journey.
I found a effective workout at home, plus I can still run when Im able to.
I found a community.
I found support.
I found out, I wasn’t alone.

I’m opening up my next bootcamp, we start Jan 1st. If your looking for a solution or needing some support this season, I’d love for you to join me. Either send me a message or drop a comment “HABITS” and I’ll send you info!

***there’s options for those of you that don’t want to use Beachbody but want community! ***
